I go with the onset of visible pregnancy is rapid in avian women, with the body still designed to lay one massive egg a-la-kiwi, but instead of calcifying the "lining" fills the womb and balloons it out while the body produces embryonic fluid so that the baby will have all the nutrients regardless of the nutrition of the mother, however the "lining" can have more nutrients sent through via the umbilical cord. Functionally, it just means avian women look seven-months pregnant for 5 months of the 9 month pregnancy, while during the lead up to birth, as the baby consumes more, the lining contracts slightly as the volume decreases. The water still breaks and contractions then begin.

Fortunately for bird women, they don't have teeth to lose during pregnancy, and this massive nutritional load meant that in the past a young woman developing an utterly ravenous appetite was a sign of her pregnancy.
